WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.400
So the example here for the study, I'm going to start with the COBALT study, which was a phase one dose escalating study for CD70-targeted allogenic CAR-T in relapsed refractory T-cell lymphoma.

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:17.560
Those are my disclosures.

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:20.480
I'm trying to focus on three areas here.

00:00:20.780 --> 00:00:25.320
First, I'll mention the obstacles in making CAR-T in general for T-cell malignancies.

00:00:25.460 --> 00:00:33.380
Then I'll give the examples of the COBALT study, which identified a new target with CD70 and has a lot of advantages.

00:00:34.060 --> 00:00:38.840
The construct of this CAR-T and some clinical evidence and what we learned from that study.

00:00:39.340 --> 00:00:45.260
And moving forward with the CAR-T landscape for now in T-cell lymphoma and the future direction.

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:48.760
So why it is difficult for CAR-T?

00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:53.820
We have great success with B-cell malignancies, which is struggling with T-cell lymphoma.

00:00:53.820 --> 00:00:55.240
And there are three areas.

00:00:55.440 --> 00:01:04.920
The first area that we are mainly struggling with is the fratricide, which basically when CAR-T and T-cell malignancies and healthy T-cells share common antigens.

00:01:05.060 --> 00:01:10.980
And you end up by doing this, the CAR-T itself attack each other while doing the production for CAR-T.

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:14.900
And that's a big problem in CAR-T and T-cell lymphoma.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:16.500
And there is a way to go around that.

00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:21.680
Other problems is the T-cell aplasia that you can develop from the CAR-T therapy.

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:25.420
Unlike B-cell aplasia, where you can replace IVIG, T-cell aplasia.

00:01:25.440 --> 00:01:33.020
Because more profound immune deficiency that can be required to do an allergenic transplant afterwards.

00:01:33.420 --> 00:01:35.600
And third, the product contaminations.

00:01:36.100 --> 00:01:42.480
You don't want to basically transduce malignant T-cells while doing the process.

00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:53.580
That will lead to the tumor escape, where we have a downgrade of the masking for the antigens of targets and lead to the T-cell lymphoma to progress.

00:01:53.700 --> 00:01:55.400
And there is a way to go.

00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:56.020
We'll go over those.

00:01:56.100 --> 00:01:57.840
We'll try to cover during my talk.

00:01:58.400 --> 00:02:01.640
So for the COBALT study, they used CD70 targets.

00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:04.660
And we learned from that a lot of lessons from the CD70.

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:07.420
CD70 is a transmembrane protein.

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:10.160
It's a part of the TNF superfamily.

00:02:10.740 --> 00:02:13.420
It's highly expressed in T-cell malignancies.

00:02:13.700 --> 00:02:17.340
More than 70% of T-cell malignancy do express CD70.

00:02:17.840 --> 00:02:20.040
Even higher in cutaneous T-cell lymphoma.

00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:25.260
But also it's expressed on activated T-cells and NKs and B-cells.

